Hi, I am the author of https://github.com/seblyng/roslyn.nvim

For a long time now, I have had some issues with being able to properly stop/restart the server from neovim, but I haven't had the time to look into what is happening until now.

So, reading the spec for the exit notification here: https://microsoft.github.io/language-server-protocol/specifications/lsp/3.17/specification/#exit

it states that the client (neovim in my example) should send an exit notification to roslyn. Roslyn should then _actually_ exit. However, looking at the implementation of the handler for the exit notification, I cannot find anything related to actually exiting the server.

As a test, I added this:

```diff
diff --git a/src/LanguageServer/Protocol/Handler/ServerLifetime/LspServiceLifeCycleManager.cs b/src/LanguageServer/Protocol/Handler/ServerLifetime/LspServiceLifeCycleManager.cs
index 0c224504a53..a7f25770d29 100644
--- a/src/LanguageServer/Protocol/Handler/ServerLifetime/LspServiceLifeCycleManager.cs
+++ b/src/LanguageServer/Protocol/Handler/ServerLifetime/LspServiceLifeCycleManager.cs
@@ -68,7 +68,9 @@ public async Task ShutdownAsync(string message = "Shutting down")
         }
     }

-    public async Task ExitAsync()
+    public Task ExitAsync()
     {
+        Environment.Exit(0);
+        return Task.CompletedTask;
     }
 }
```

and now it works exactly as expected for me.

I am not sure if the above snippet will cause any issues with for example the test suite, but I do believe this is an issue where the LSP specification is not followed as it should, and it requires a change here.

Consider the following code:
```cs
interface I1
{
    int F {get;}
}

class C12
{
    object Value => throw null;

    static bool Test1((object, int) u)
    {
        return u is (C12 and I1 and { F: 1 }, 2) or (I1 and { F: 1 or 2 }, 1);
    }   
}
```

Examine code generated for `Test`. The following is a de-compilation output produced by https://lab.razor.fyi.
It looks like the property reads at `label1` and `label2` redundant. The value read at `label1` isn't even used.
The value read at `label2` is used, but we could simply use value from local `f`, assigned at `label0`.  
Note that ```i2 = (I1)item;``` operations on lines preceding `label1` and `label2` are redundant as well.
Even if the property reads were necessary, The value is already available in local `i`.
```cs
	private static bool Test1(ValueTuple<object, int> u)
	{
		object item = u.Item1;
		C12 c = item as C12;
		int item2;
		int f2;
		if (c != null)
		{
			I1 i = c as I1;
			if (i != null)
			{
label0:
				int f = i.F;
				I1 i2;
				if (f == 1)
				{
					item2 = u.Item2;
					if (item2 != 2)
					{
						i2 = (I1)item;
label1:
						f2 = i2.F;
						goto IL_0081;
					}
					goto IL_0088;
				}
				i2 = (I1)item;
label2:
				f2 = i2.F;
				goto IL_0074;
			}
		}
		else
		{
			I1 i2 = item as I1;
			if (i2 != null)
			{
				f2 = i2.F;
				if (f2 != 1)
				{
					goto IL_0074;
				}
				goto IL_0079;
			}
		}
		goto IL_008d;
		IL_0079:
		item2 = u.Item2;
		goto IL_0081;
		IL_008d:
		return false;
		IL_0074:
		if (f2 == 2)
		{
			goto IL_0079;
		}
		goto IL_008d;
		IL_0088:
		return true;
		IL_0081:
		if (item2 == 1)
		{
			goto IL_0088;
		}
		goto IL_008d;
	}
```

